headline: The Week in Numbers: hot valuations, a YouTube payout
summary: STORY: From hot valuations to a YouTube payout, this is the Week in Numbers.:: Week in Numbers:: $500 billion$500 billion is what OpenAI could be worth.A source told Reuters that the company behind ChatGPT, has reportedly reached the valuation following a deal in which current and former employees sold roughly $6.6 billion worth of shares.It underscores OpenAI's rapid gains in both users and revenue.:: 497,099497,099 is the number of vehicles Tesla sold in the three months to September. Tesla announced the record quarterly deliveries on Thursday.But there are concerns that an expiration of the U.S. tax credit for EVs could turn a rush of buying into a trickle.The Elon Musk-led carmaker went all in to drive sales before the withdrawal of the $7,500 federal tax credit.It used a combination of discounts, financing deals, and social media ads.:: 2.77%2.77% was the rise in European healthcare stocks on Wednesday - their biggest daily rise since April. It came a day after U.S.-based drugmaker Pfizer and President Trump announced an agreement to lower prescription drug prices in the Medicaid program in exchange for tariff relief.5%Shares of Spotify were down more than 5% Tuesday morning.That was after the news that its founder Daniel Ek was stepping down as CEO.The streaming giant is reshaping its leadership team to fend off rivals and shore up profits.Ek will become executive chairman in January to focus on long-term strategy and capital allocation.::$24.5 millionAlphabet-owned YouTube has agreed to pay $24.5 million to settle a lawsuit that Donald Trump brought against the company.It was over the suspension of his account following the January 2021 U.S. Capitol riots, a court filing showed.Trump said in a post on his Truth Social account, "This massive victory proves Big Tech censorship has consequences."
